TY  - JOUR
AB  - Cross-section data often show that the wealth of the elderly increases with age, suggesting that the life cycle hypothesis of consumption should include a bequest motive for saving. I propose a model of bequests, and a test for a bequest motive. Empirical findings are that in a ten-year panel data set, the elderly dissaved, in contradiction to most cross-section results. The test offers no support for a bequest motive.
